<header class="display-wrap pt-0">
	<h3 class="">Accessibility</h3>
	<p class="body fs-4 lh-4 slate-100 mb-8">
		ActiveCampaign Design is devoted to providing everyone with the ability to use our products regardless of impairment. Below we outline our primary goals to address a few of these impairments. Each provide a unique set of challenges that we have strived to improve upon throughout our products.
	</p>
	<p class="fs-6 fw-600 pt-6">Process</p>
	<div class="grid g-cols gap-l mt-6">
		<div class="g-col-3">
			<%= image_tag "access-identify.svg" %>
			<p class="fs-4 fw-500">Identify</p>
			<p class="fs-3 lh-3 slate-80">Those who have impairments and need special accessibility throughout our products require different solutions. </p>
		</div>
		<div class="g-col-3">
			<%= image_tag "access-plan.svg" %>
			<p class="fs-4 fw-500">Plan</p>
			<p class="fs-3 lh-3 slate-80">Check and insure all accessibility guidelines are met before implementing a new or updated solution.</p>
		</div>
		<div class="g-col-3">
			<%= image_tag "access-adapt.svg" %>
			<p class="fs-4 fw-500">Adapt</p>
			<p class="fs-3 lh-3 slate-80">Implement globally accessible solutions into our products using appropriate guidelines.</p>
		</div>
		<div class="g-col-3">
			<%= image_tag "access-unify.svg" %>
			<p class="fs-4 fw-500">Unify</p>
			<p class="fs-3 lh-3 slate-80">Create a unified, inclusive experience throughout our products and services.</p>
		</div>
	</div>
</header>
<%= render "sectionnav" %>
<section id="checklist">
	<div class="display-wrap separator">
		<h5>Checklist</h5>
		<p class="fs-4 lh-4">Those with color blindness require a unique set of distinguishable colors, while those with low sight require easily identifying colors for actionable elements. For those with little to no sight abilities there needs to be a specific set of standards in place so that they can still use our products. Below, we go through the various ways in which we combat impairments throughout our products here at ActiveCampaign with a easy to reference checklist.</p>

		<div class="pt-10"><%= image_tag "Icon/icon-contrast.svg" %></div>
		<p class="fs-6 fw-600"> Color Contrast</p>
		<p class="fs-4 lh-4">Throughout our products our primary focus is adhering to <a href="https://www.w3.org/TR/WCAG20/" target="_blank">WCAG AA</a> (4.5:1) with some exceptions. For more information on how to use color to meet this standard, refer to <a href="/brand/colors">our colors page</a> for a complete guide.</p>

		<div class="pt-10"><%= image_tag "Icon/icon-color_blind.svg" %></div>
		<p class="fs-6 fw-600"> Color Blindness</p>
		<p class="fs-4 lh-4 pb-8"><sup>1</sup> About 8% of all men are suffering from color blindness while another 1 in 200 women suffering from it as well. This requires a unique set of colors throughout our palette to insure each are easily distinguishable from one another. There are three main types of color vision deficiency: protan, deutan, and tritan defects. These three types are shown below using our <a href="/brand/colors/">primary color palette</a>.</p>

		<div class=""><%= image_tag "access-color-normal", width: "412" %></div>
		<div class="pt-8"><%= image_tag "access-color-protan", width: "412" %></div>
		<div class="pt-8"><%= image_tag "access-color-deuter", width: "412" %></div>
		<div class="pt-8"><%= image_tag "access-color-tritan", width: "412" %></div>
		<div class="mt-10">
			<p class="fs-2 lh-2"><sup>1</sup> Colour Blindness, <a href="www.colourblindawareness.org/colour-blindness/" target="_blank">www.colourblindawareness.org/colour-blindness/</a>
		</div>

		<div class="pt-10"><%= image_tag "Icon/icon-novision.svg" %></div>
		<p class="fs-6 fw-600">Low Vision / No Vision</p>
		<p class="fs-4 lh-4 pb-2">Ensuring those with more severe visual impairments have complete control and access to our products, the following should be considered in any case:</p>
		<ul class="fs-4 lh-4 pl-6">
			<li class="pb-4">If using an image, provide an adequate <a href="https://www.w3schools.com/TAGS/att_alt.asp" target="_blank" title="ALT attribute">ALT attribute</a> for description and include an <a href="http://w3c.github.io/html-reference/aria/aria.html" target="_blank">ARIA attribute</a> for screen readers when necessary. </li>
			<li class="pb-4">Controls should be clearly identifiable via all their states and accessible for screen readers. They should be easy to navigate using <a href="#keyboard-control">keyboard controls</a> and <a href="/brand/colors">colors</a> should adhere to our <a href="/brand/colors#usage">color usage guide</a>.</li>
			<li class="pb-4">Controls should always be consistent and predictable. </li>
			<li class="pb-4">Text sizes and line heights should be sized appropriately and have the ability to be adjusted if needed by the user.</li>
			<li class="pb-4">Text colors should be chosen carefully. Rever to our typography color guide for more information.</li>
			<li class="pb-4">Navigational elements should be clearly identifiable and understandable by a screen reader. They should also be easy to use via <a href="#keyboard-control">keyboard controls</a>.</li>
			<li class="pb-4">Form elements and user input controls should be easily identifiable by a screen reader and easy to navigate using <a href="#keyboard-control">keyboard controls</a>. </li>
			<li class="">Visual feedback should be described and accessible by a screen reader. Examples include loading states, notifications and status updates, animations and control state changes such as focus/active or hover.</li>
		</ul>

		<div class="pt-10"><%= image_tag "Icon/icon-cogs.svg" %></div>
		<p class="fs-6 fw-600">Motor, Neurological or Cognitive</p>
		<p class="fs-4 lh-4 pb-2">As with severe visual impairments, motor, neurological and cognitive impairments can have many challenges for accessibility. Below the following should be considered in any case:</p>
		<ul class="fs-4 lh-4 pl-6">
			<li class="pb-4">Navigation should be consistent with other instances and easy to understand. </li>
			<li class="pb-4">Controls and inputs should not require precision to activate/focus or require a mouse exclusively. Each control should be keyboard accessible. Refer to the section below <a href="#keyboard-control">Keyboard Control</a> for more information.</li>
		</ul>

	</div>
</section>
<section id="keyboard-control">
	<div class="display-wrap separator">
		<h5>Keyboard Control</h5>
		<p class="fs-4 lh-4">Users with motor, cognitive, neurological or visual disabilities may require the use of a keyboard exclusively. When developing and designing our web products, keyboard control should be of utmost highest priority. By providing these simple solutions we allow these users to experience our products as well as others.</p>

		<div class="mt-8"><%= image_tag "access-keyboard-nav1", width: "100%" %></div>
		<div class="mt-4"><%= image_tag "access-keyboard-nav2", width: "100%" %></div>
		<ol class="fs-4 lh-4 pl-5 mb-10">
			<li class="pb-4">Use proper focus states to provide visual feedback. Included should be ARIA tags to describe the element as well as a title.</li>
			<li class="pb-4">Tabbing flow should be natural just like reading, from left to right top to bottom to each element on the screen.</li>	
			<li>If on-hover dropdown menus are used, ensure a user can tab to and into and out of each menu and user arrow controls inside.</li>	
		</ol>

		<p class="fs-6 fw-600">Focus States</p>
		<p class="fs-4 lh-4 pb-2">Controllable elements should provide visual feedback when focused. The focus state provides the knowledge that the element is currently highlighted/active. A screen reader will also read any descriptive tag when an element has been focused. Ensure all interactive elements have proper focus states. Refer to the examples below.</p>
		<div class="mt-4"><%= image_tag "access-focus1", width: "656" %></div>

		<p class="fs-6 fw-600 mt-10">Custom Blocks</p>
		<p class="fs-4 lh-4 pb-2">Blocks like cards or elements that contain non-native interaction pose a difficulty for keyboard users to navigate to. Ensure elements like these contain tabindex attributes and are available for navigation.</p>
		<div class="mt-4"><%= image_tag "access-focus2", width: "827" %></div>
		<ol class="fs-4 lh-4 pl-5">
			<li class="pb-4">Custom blocks that are clickable should also be able to be focused and interacted with in a natural manner.</li>
			<li>Tabbing flow should be natural just like reading, from left to right top to bottom to each element on the screen.</li>	
		</ol>
	</div>
</section>
<section id="audible-feedback">
	<div class="display-wrap separator">
		<h5>Audible Feedback</h5>
		<p class="fs-4 lh-4">Screen readers are an important part to those with extreme visual disabilities. They allow the use of websites and web products by using audible feedback. Combining the keyboard control requirements with proper accessible markup, a user with such a disability can access our content the same as others. When building our products please consider the guidelines below. </p>
		<div class="grid g-cols gap-l">
			<div class="g-col-6">
				<div class="mt-6">
					<%= image_tag "access-audible1", width: "468" %>
					<div class="bs-solid bw-1 w-50 mt-6"></div>
					<p class="fs-3 lh-3">Custom elements that have no descriptive purpose, although important cannot be understood by screen readers and will be skipped.</p>
				</div>
